  short_description: Apartament o allotjament al centre.
  description: |
    Apartament cèntric ideal per explorar Bratislava a peu, situat en el cor del barri vell. Aquest allotjament ofereix accés fàcil a les principals atraccions turístiques com el Castell de Bratislava, la Plaça Principal i el Pont SNP amb les seves vistes panoràmiques. La ubicació estratègica permet als visitants gaudir de l'atmosfera històrica de la ciutat while having modern amenities and a comfortable base for exploring Slovak capital.

    The apartment provides easy walking distance to Bratislava's main attractions including Old Town Hall, St. Martin's Cathedral, Michael's Gate, and numerous restaurants and cafés serving traditional Slovak cuisine. Guests can enjoy morning coffee in nearby Hviezdoslavovo Square before heading to castle for panoramic Danube views. Evening strolls along the Danube promenade are just steps away, perfect for experiencing Bratislava's blend of medieval charm and modern riverside development.

    This accommodation choice offers authentic local experience, allowing visitors to immerse themselves in Bratislava's daily rhythm while having comfortable retreat after days spent exploring castle hill, wandering medieval streets, or enjoying boat trips on the Danube. The central location provides excellent public transportation connections for day trips to Devin Castle or other nearby attractions.
- id: castell-de-bratislava
  name: Castell de Bratislava
  zone: Bratislava
  category: Castell
  coordinates:
  - 48.1421086
  - 17.1002348
  google_maps: https://maps.google.com/?cid=3446134353892385081
  images:
  - https://www.visitbratislava.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/letecka-vychod-slnka-hrad-800x533.jpg
  short_description: Castell emblemàtic amb vistes al Danubi.
  description: |
    Perched 85 meters above the Danube River, Bratislava Castle dominates Slovakia's capital with its distinctive white walls and four corner towers. More than an architectural landmark, this hilltop fortress chronicles Central European history from Celtic settlements through medieval kingdoms, Habsburg rule, and modern Slovak independence. The castle hill has hosted settlements for over 4,500 years, evolving from 9th-century Great Moravian fortifications through Gothic palace constructions in the 15th century, Renaissance rebuilding in the 16th century, to baroque magnificence under Maria Theresa in the 18th century.

    The castle served as the main residence of Hungarian kings during the Ottoman occupation of Hungary, making Bratislava (then Pressburg) the capital of the Kingdom of Hungary from 1536 to 1783. During this golden age, the castle witnessed the coronation of 19 kings and queens in the city below. The complex included extensive fortifications, residential buildings, and treasury facilities. After a devastating fire in 1811 left it in ruins, the castle was meticulously reconstructed in the 1950s during the communist era, becoming home to the Slovak National Museum.

    Today, visitors can explore the castle's historical exhibitions, enjoy panoramic views of Bratislava and the Danube, and walk through the beautifully restored courtyards. The castle's crown-like silhouette against the sky has become the symbol of Slovakia's capital, offering a tangible connection to centuries of royal power and cultural significance that shaped Central European history. The surrounding castle district provides a perfect starting point for exploring Bratislava's medieval Old Town and understanding the city's strategic importance throughout history.
- id: marketplace-mileti-ova
  name: Marketplace Miletičova
  zone: Bratislava
  category: Mercat
  coordinates:
