- id: hlavn-n-mestie
  name: Hlavné námestie
  zone: Bratislava
  category: Plaça
  coordinates:
  - 48.143508
  - 17.1084789
  google_maps: https://maps.google.com/?cid=6774207005440058464
  images:
  - https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Hlavn%C3%A9_n%C3%A1mestie-The_napoleonic_soldier%2C_Old_Town_Hall_and_Roland_Fountain-Bratislava.JPG/330px-Hlavn%C3%A9_n%C3%A1mestie-The_napoleonic_soldier%2C_Old_Town_Hall_and_Roland_Fountain-Bratislava.JPG
  short_description: Plaça principal del centre històric.
  description: |
    Hlavné námestie, or Main Square, forms the historic heart of Bratislava's Old Town and has been the city's central gathering point for over 600 years. This picturesque square showcases a fascinating blend of architectural styles, with the dominant Old Town Hall serving as its centerpiece. The square's irregular shape and colorful Renaissance and Baroque buildings create a distinctly Central European atmosphere that has witnessed countless historic events, markets, and celebrations throughout Bratislava's long history.

    The square's most significant landmarks include the Roland Fountain, an impressive replica of the original 1572 fountain that symbolized city privileges and market rights, and the Old Town Hall complex with its distinctive tower offering panoramic views. Perhaps most intriguing is the Napoleonic Soldier statue, a curious monument commemorating the French army's gaze upon Bratislava in 1805 when Napoleon observed the city from this very spot. The square also features various cafés and restaurants whose outdoor terraces spill onto the cobblestones, creating a vibrant atmosphere especially during summer months.

    Throughout history, Hlavné námestie has been the stage for royal proclamations, public executions, coronation processions, and today hosts Christmas markets and cultural festivals. The square's surrounding buildings house important museums, shops, and the city's oldest pharmacy, dating back to the 16th century. Walking across these cobblestones offers visitors a direct connection to Bratislava's medieval past while enjoying the lively energy of modern Slovak culture and cuisine.
