- id: michael-s-gate
  name: Michael’s Gate
  zone: Bratislava
  category: Porta
  coordinates:
  - 48.14517
  - 17.10673
  google_maps: https://maps.google.com/?cid=11536058061704934464
  images:
  - https://www.strassederkaiserundkoenige.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/500x300_2.-Michaeler-Tor_c-MS-Agency.jpg
  short_description: Porta medieval, entrada principal de la ciutat antiga.
  description: |
    Michael's Gate stands as the only surviving medieval gate from Bratislava's original fortifications, marking the northern entrance to the historic Old Town. Built around 1300, this iconic gate was one of four entrances that controlled access to the medieval city, alongside the now-demolished Laurinc Gate (eastern), Vydrica Gate (western), and Fishermen's Gate (southern). The gate's impressive 51-meter-high tower has become one of Bratislava's most recognizable landmarks, crowned with its distinctive green copper roof and statue of Saint Michael slaying a dragon.

    The tower's architecture evolved through multiple phases, starting as a three-storey structure and being reinforced and elevated between the 16th and 18th centuries. During the 1750s, the gate received its baroque exterior makeover that visitors see today, including the addition of the iconic statue of Saint Michael. The gate complex included sophisticated defensive features like a barbican, a bridge over the fortification moat, and a curved street between the main tower and outer gate. These elements created a formidable obstacle for potential invaders while controlling movement in and out of the city.

    Today, visitors can climb to the top of Michael's Tower for breathtaking panoramic views across Bratislava's red rooftops and to the castle hill. Inside, the gate houses the Museum of Weapons, showcasing medieval armor and weaponry that once defended the city. Walking through Michael's Gate is literally stepping back in time, following the same path that merchants, nobles, and kings traveled when Bratislava served as the capital of the Kingdom of Hungary. The gate represents not just architectural beauty, but the resilience and strategic importance that defined Bratislava's medieval history.
