- id: st-martin-s-cathedral
  name: St. Martin's Cathedral
  zone: Bratislava
  category: Església
  coordinates:
  - 48.14202
  - 17.10476
  google_maps: https://maps.google.com/?cid=14402334000592657117
  images:
  - https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcS7kk0BAEJc9Q55ObpzHE24gKt3zUpHJOa1RQ&s
  short_description: Catedral gòtica de coronacions.
  description: |
    St. Martin's Cathedral stands as one of Slovakia's most significant historical and religious buildings, serving as the coronation church for Hungarian kings during Bratislava's golden age as capital of the Kingdom of Hungary. This magnificent three-nave Gothic cathedral was built on the site of an earlier Romanesque church dedicated to the Holy Savior, which dated back to 1221. The present Gothic structure, consecrated in 1452, became integral part of city's fortifications, with its tower serving as a defensive bastion protecting Bratislava's northern approaches.

    Between 1563 and 1830, this cathedral witnessed the coronation of 19 kings and queens of Hungary, including the famous Habsburg queen Maria Theresa. These ceremonies transformed Bratislava into one of Europe's most important coronation cities, with elaborate processions and celebrations that would last for days. The cathedral's interior, measuring 69.37 meters long, 22.85 meters wide, and 16.02 meters high, features grand architectural details including a preserved tympanum relief of the Holy Trinity and four historic chapels dedicated to various saints and nobility.

    Perhaps the cathedral's most striking feature is its 85-meter-high tower, crowned with a gilded replica of St. Stephen's crown weighing 150 kilograms. This golden crown has become the symbol of Bratislava's coronation legacy and can be seen from many points across the city. Today, visitors can explore the cathedral's rich history through its museum collection, attend services, and imagine the elaborate coronation ceremonies that once filled these sacred halls with the pageantry of European royalty. The cathedral remains an active place of worship while serving as a tangible connection to centuries of Hungarian and Slovak royal history.
